          "title": "Testimony, recognition, and confession — the inaugural week",
          "body": "The narrative (1:19-51) demonstrates in story form what the prologue declared in summary. The Baptist subordinates himself five times — not Christ, not Elijah, not the Prophet, only a voice, not worthy to untie His sandal (1:19-27). Then his positive testimony: \"Behold, the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world!\" (1:29). The Spirit-attestation at Jesus's baptism (1:32-34) seals the witness. The chapter's final movement (1:35-51) traces discipleship as a chain reaction — John points to Jesus, Andrew finds Peter, Jesus finds Philip, Philip finds Nathanael. Confessions stack: Rabbi (1:38), Messiah (1:41), Him of whom Moses wrote (1:45), Son of God, King of Israel (1:49). The chapter closes with Jesus's first solemn *amēn amēn*: you will see the heavens opened and angels ascending and descending on the Son of Man (1:51) — claiming for Himself the role of Jacob's ladder, the meeting point of heaven and earth."
